<DocSection Title="Scaffold your first project">
    <p>Pick a folder, create a new directory for your project, and run the template:</p>

    <DocSnippet Name="ScaffoldFirstProject" Language="bash" />

    <p>
        The <code>-n</code> (name) flag is used as both the solution name and the root
        namespace for every project the template generates. Choose carefully —
        renaming after the fact is mechanical but tedious.
    </p>

    <p>
        Two parameters are <b>required</b> by the template:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>--includeSampleApp true</code> — generates a fully working sample
            (the StockPlusPlus inventory app) so you have something to run immediately.
            Set to <code>false</code> for an empty skeleton.</li>
        <li><code>--shiftIdentityHostingType Internal</code> — hosts ShiftIdentity
            inside the same API process. Use <code>External</code> if you already
            run a separate ShiftIdentity instance.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        The template accepts several other optional parameters. The next page
        (<MudLink Href="/get-started/template-parameters">Template parameters</MudLink>)
        explains each one in detail.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Build and verify">
    <p>From the project directory, restore packages and build:</p>

    <DocSnippet Name="BuildProject" Language="bash" />

    <p>
        A clean build means the template, all NuGet packages, and your local SDK
        are aligned. If you see errors at this stage, they are almost always one of:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>An older .NET SDK — confirm with <code>dotnet --version</code> that you're on .NET 10 or newer.</li>
        <li>NuGet feed issues — check <code>nuget.config</code> for any private feeds your machine can't reach.</li>
        <li>A previous template install pinned to an older version — reinstall with the <code>@@*</code> suffix shown above.</li>
    </ul>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Warning">
        Do <b>not</b> run the app yet. The generated project expects a database that
        doesn't exist until you run migrations. The next page covers running the
        sample end-to-end, including the database setup.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

